    "result": {"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<h2 id=\"jvms-memory-area\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#jvms-memory-area\" aria-label=\"jvms memory area permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>JVM's Memory Area</h2>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 800px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/f040bf807561367ced3aa18d2b7856ad/6a068/jvm-architecture.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 75%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"jvm architecture\"\n        title=\"jvm architecture\"\n        src=\"/static/f040bf807561367ced3aa18d2b7856ad/4b190/jvm-architecture.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/f040bf807561367ced3aa18d2b7856ad/e07e9/jvm-architecture.jpg 200w,\n/static/f040bf807561367ced3aa18d2b7856ad/066f9/jvm-architecture.jpg 400w,\n/static/f040bf807561367ced3aa18d2b7856ad/4b190/jvm-architecture.jpg 800w,\n/static/f040bf807561367ced3aa18d2b7856ad/6a068/jvm-architecture.jpg 960w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/how-many-types-of-memory-areas-are-allocated-by-jvm/\">Image source</a></p>\n<h2 id=\"the-stack\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#the-stack\" aria-label=\"the stack permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>The stack</h2>\n<p>Each thread running in the Java virtual machine has its own thread stack, which contains information about which methods the thread has called (the call stack)</p>\n<p>It also contains <strong>all the local variables</strong> and parameters.</p>\n<p>Primitive local variables are fully stored on the thread stack.</p>\n<p>Reference local variables point to objects in the heap</p>\n<h2 id=\"the-heap\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#the-heap\" aria-label=\"the heap permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>The heap</h2>\n<p>The heap contains all objects created in your Java application, regardless of which thread created the object.</p>\n<p>It does not matter if an object was created and assigned to a local variable, or created as a member variable of another object, it will be stored on the heap.</p>\n<p>If an object is not referenced by any reference variable, it becomes garbage!</p>\n<p>From time to time, the JVM will trigger the garbage collector to remove these unused objects from memory.</p>\n<h2 id=\"demo\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#demo\" aria-label=\"demo permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Demo</h2>\n<p>Here is a step-by-step demo of how the stack and the heap are used when executing a Java program: <a href=\"/stack-heap-demo.m4v\">video</a></p>","frontmatter":{"slug":"/java/memory-model","title":"Java Memory Model","course":"Programming Project 2021/22","previous":"/java/variables-parameters","next":"/exceptions/exceptions","chapter":4,"section":4,"module":"How Java Works","banner":null}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/java/memory-model"}},
